<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> He did not argue with your evidence but with the fact that it is/isnt aggro reducing, and it DOES glow on slow and any other spell that causes aggro... I think it even glows on heals, but I will have to test that with a cleric.... more on that when I get the test done. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sigh.  No the earring does not glow on any spell that causes aggro, and no it definitely does not glow on slow spells.  Just to show you how dedicated I am to proving the facts, I had my mage friend give an earring to a shaman in my guild to try it.  He did not get a glow message when he casted slow.  Want more evidence? Fine.<br>
<br>
This is parsed from EQCaster via the spell data file.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Jolum's Major Abatement<br>
1: Lowers mana cost up to 15%<br>
2: Restriction: Spells level 60 and lower<br>
3: Restriction: 'Detrimental' spells only<br>
4: Addition: 'Hit Points (HP)' spells included</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Look at 1: Lowers mana cost up to 15%.  Nope that doesnt say lowers aggro.<br>
<br>
Look at 3 and 4.  Detrimental and Hit point spells only.  That means that the earring effect only works with spells that directly change a target's HP in a detrimental fashion.  If you look at other spells in the spell data, they are mostly either listed as either &quot;Beneficial&quot; or &quot;Detrimental.&quot;  Slows are listed as detrimental, however they do not affect hit points.  Heals do affect hit points, however they are listed as beneficial.<br>
<br>
